Big portions, lots of seating (which is maybe only a plus for someone trying to plan a big dinner or if you're looking for that suburban America experience!) and friendly staff don't save the mediocre food and some puzzling pricing. First, I'd like to address the complementary potato chips and sauce. The chips were light and seemed house-made, but had an old grease taste and were room temperature. The sauce tasted like marinara sauce. That and potato chips is not something I'd had before, and it's not something I'd like to have again. I ordered the chicken stew with a side of rice and beans, and a side of patacones. The stew was bountiful, but bland. Because it was bone in chicken, I kept getting bits of bone and gristle with each bite. The red beans were also disappointingly bland; the rice was fine. Finally the pricing. Without a drink my dinner was $24. That's not cheap and at that price range there's plenty of options in Brooklyn.

My husband and I were regulars at El Viejo Yayo.  The manager knew us and always greeted us upon arrival.  Tonight he wasn’t there, but didn’t think anything of it.  We ordered our food and I ordered grilled pork chops.  They came out fried.  Ok, no big deal, I’ll let it slide even though my husband ate without me.  The waitress told me 5-7 minutes.  15 minutes later she comes out with burnt grilled pork chops.  How could they even leave the kitchen?  They were burnt and dry as a bone.  That was it,  we got the check and left.  Needless to say, I left not only hungry but annoyed.  The manager that used to be there ran a tight ship.  The food and service was excellent.   After reading some other reviews, I’m assuming he is no longer there and this is just the way it is now.  So disappointed!  Definitely wouldn’t recommend and won’t be back.
